member.remarks:
We recommend you use this type like:

static int[] Example()
{
    using scoped var list = new ValueList<int>(10);
    list.Add(3);
    list.Add(6);
    return [.. list];
}

We recommend you use this type like:

static int[] Example()
{
    using scoped var list = new ValueList<int>(10);
    list.Add(3);
    list.Add(6);
    return [.. list];
}

Please note that the type uses unmanaged memory, so you must use  keyword
to release unmanaged memory when you don't use it, such as:

using scoped var list = (ValueList<int>)[1, 2, 3, 4];

// ...

This method does not use casting to make the target  value to be converted into a  value.
If the type  has implemented , C# language will allow this type
using -like operators  && and  ||
to determine multiple  values are  or  via the specified way
to be checked. This is just like C programming language rule - allowing any implicit casts from an integer to a boolean value like:

if (integer) // integer != 0 in C and op_True(integer) in C#
{
    // ...
}

The backing implementation is like the following code in C#:

struct Int32
{
    public static bool operator true(int value) => value != 0;
    public sttaic bool operator false(int value) => value == 0;
}

You can use this type like this:

scoped var sb = new StringHandler(initialCapacity: 100);
sb.Append("Hello");
sb.Append(',');
sb.Append("World");
sb.Append('!');

Console.WriteLine(sb.ToStringAndClear());

target.remarks:
					Beginning with C# 7, we can customize the return value type of a  variable
					if we implement a parameterless method called GetPinnableReference, returning by
					 or . For example, if we hold a fixed buffer
					of element type:


class ExampleType
{
    private fixed short _maskList[100];

    public ref readonly short GetPinnableReference() => ref _maskList[0];
}


					We can use  statement to define a variable of type *
					as the left-value.


var instance = new ExampleType();
fixed (short* ptr = instance)
{
    // Operation here.
}

member.remarks:
This method can be used for removing the last separator in a whole string, split by separators.
For example:

const string separator = ", "; // Defines a separator.

scoped var sb = new StringHandler(); // Creates a string concatenator.
foreach (var element in list)
{
    sb.Append(element); // Append the element.
    sb.Append(separator); // Append the separator.
}

// Use the method 'RemoveFromEnd' to remove the last separator.
sb.RemoveFromEnd(separator.Length);

// Get the final string value and release the temporarily allocated memory.
return sb.ToStringAndClear();

This method allows you using  loop to iterate this value:

foreach (var bit in 17)
{
    // Do something...
}

For example:

byte value = 0b00010111;
foreach (int bitPos in value.SkipSetBit(2))
{
    yield return bitPos + 1;
}

You will get 3 and 5, because all set bit positions are 0, 1, 2 and 4, and we have skipped
two of them, so the result set bit positions to iterate on are only 2 and 4.

remarks.para:
The original way to declare a type with primary constructor is like:

public readonly struct Color(byte a, byte r, byte g, byte b)
{
    public byte A { get; } = a;
    public byte R { get; } = r;
    public byte G { get; } = g;
    public byte B { get; } = b;
}

Via this attribute type, we can simplify the code:

public readonly partial struct Color([DataMember] byte a, [DataMember] byte r, [DataMember] byte g, [DataMember] byte b);

Such code is equivalent to the original one.

The original way to declare a type with primary constructor is like:

public readonly struct Color(byte a, byte r, byte g, byte b)
{
    public byte A { get; } = a;
    public byte R { get; } = r;
    public byte G { get; } = g;
    public byte B { get; } = b;
}

Via this attribute type, we can simplify the code:

public readonly partial struct Color([DataMember] byte a, [DataMember] byte r, [DataMember] byte g, [DataMember] byte b);

Such code is equivalent to the original one.

Also, you can set the first character as lower or upper case via symbols < and >. If this property is "_<@", the generated member will be like:
private int _parameter = parameter;
where "<@" means the generated member name will use lower case for its first character.

member.remarks:
You can use this attribute to create a field:

[ImplicitField]
public int Property
{
    get => _property;
    set => _property ??= value;
}

You may not write code to create field _property. This attribute will make source generators generate it.

